nodes.text: David Davis : I would have done the same thing, frankly, in those circumstances

David Davis : I don't think Boris should have done much different

Boris Johnson's nonaction against Matt Hancock was or was not yet another missed opportunity to show leadership
AudienceMember 20210707QT01 : set the standard for social distancing
Boris Johnson's non-action was or was not yet another missed opportunity to set the standard for social distancing
David Davis : it was plain that Matt was going to go
it was plain that Matt Hancock was going to go
David Davis : I'm just reading his mind the same way you would
David Davis is just reading Boris Johnson's mind the same way you would
Fiona Bruce : So you are saying, David, you would have done the same thing
David Davis would have done the same thing as Boris Johnson in regards to Matt Hancock
Andy Burnham : I don't agree with David on this
Andy Burnham : you need a prime minister to lead from the front at any time
you need a prime minister to lead from the front at any time
when families cannot see loved ones who are dying in hospitals is exactly the moment that the Prime Minister needs to set the standards that the country has to live by
Andy Burnham : This idea of one rule for them, one rule for everyone else, was introduced by the handling of the Dominic Cummings trip to Barnard Castle
this idea of one rule for them, one rule for everyone else, was introduced by the handling of the Dominic Cummings trip to Barnard Castle
Fiona Bruce : We know what he said
David Davis : He's an ex-journalist
Boris Johnson's an ex-journalist
David Davis : He knows he is talking about the fate of two families and six children, and so on
Boris Johnson knows he is talking about the fate of two families and six children, and so on
David Davis : what he was doing was creating time for the -- for Matt Hancock to make his own decision
what Boris Johnson was doing was creating time for Matt Hancock to make his own decision
David Davis : That's what I suspect was going on
David Davis suspects that Boris Johnson was creating time for Matt Hancock to make his own decision was what was going on
David Davis : if a Prime Minister shows some loyalty, even perhaps unwise loyalty to a subordinate, I think that's a good thing
Andy Burnham : I get the increasing impression it is impossible to get sacked from this government
Andy Burnham gets the increasing impression it is impossible to get sacked from this government
Andy Burnham : You can breach the ministerial code
you can breach the ministerial code
you can give contracts to your friends
Andy Burnham : What would it take, actually, to get sacked?
it is impossible to get sacked from this government
setting the right standards is particularly important at a time like this
Andy Burnham : that many families have had not being able to see loved ones
it was brought up in Question Time that many families have had not being able to see loved ones
AudienceMember 20210708QT03 : I'm in total agreement with people who find it absurd that we have to wait for a Tory minister to do the honourable thing and resign
AudienceMember 20210708QT03 is in total agreement with people who find it absurd that we have to wait for a Tory minister to do the honourable thing and resign
AudienceMember 20210708QT03 : It is yet another example that Boris Johnson either has no conception of moral standards in public office
the fact that we have to wait for someone to resign is yet another example that Boris Johnson has no conception of moral standards in public office
AudienceMember 20210708QT06 : This isn't about the whistle-blower
this isn't about the whistle-blower
AudienceMember 20210708QT04 : David hit the nail on the head there that Boris is treating this as an old boys' club
David Davis hit the nail on the head there that Boris is running the government as an old boys' club
AudienceMember 20210708QT06 : What is it that you have to do to be sacked for action to be taken
to be sacked or action to be taken you have to do xxx
AudienceMember 20210708QT06 : I think in terms of David Davis's comments around there's nothing you would have done differently
AudienceMember 20210708QT06 thinks in terms of David Davis's comments around there's nothing you would have done differently
AudienceMember 20210708QT04 : I care about him giving contracts to people who haven't gone through proper channels, giving jobs to friends and treating the public with blatant disregard
AudienceMember 20210708QT04 cares about Matt Hancock giving contracts to people who haven't gone through proper channels, giving jobs to friends and treating the public with blatant disregard
Matt Hancock should have been sacked the moment the issues came out
Chika Russell : For myself as a business leader, my team look to me for direction
AudienceMember 20210708QT05 : David Davis put it quite succinctly
Madeline Grant : What the government must, must make sure of is that the way the education system was dealt with has to be really addressed properly
Madeline Grant : now that we know a virus of some sort does come up every so often
now that we know a virus of some sort does come up every so often
Fiona Bruce : Some think we will, some don't
AudienceMember 20210708QT05 : He quite possibly lost his family
Matt Hancock quite possibly lost his family

it took the whistle-blower something like 7 weeks to put the story about the scandal into a tabloid newspaper because of xxx
Andy Burnham : We had another thing this week
Andy Burnham : that top business executives could escape quarantine
the thing this week was that top business executives could escape quarantine
Andy Burnham : Some are living by some rules
some people are living by some rules

that top business executives could escape quarantine is a clear example of how there are huge double standards

that top business executives could escape quarantine was one opportunity for Boris Johnson to stand up and be counted
that top business executives could escape quarantine was one opportunity for Boris Johnson to show us he does have a moral compass
AudienceMember 20210708QT02 : There is a litany of poor behaviour
there is a litany of poor behaviour

Fiona Bruce : why should we follow the rules when we have seen those in the highest office not doing so
xxx is why we should follow the rules when we have seen those in the highest office not doing so
Benjamin Zephaniah : Boris Johnson was a journalist
Boris Johnson was a journalist

when people are breaking the rules they are referring to Dominic Cummings, all these kinds of things
Benjamin Zephaniah : what hope have we got for the rest of the people
Fiona Bruce : what does it mean to live with the virus
Andy Burnham : You have to keep one of those
you have to keep either distancing or masks
you have to think about people who will feel worried about being out there with people without masks
it is better to keep the masks requirement

we need to maintain some restrictions

we cannot afford to go back
wearing masks, for instance, is a small imposition that should be further maintained
Madeline Grant : we should remain wearing masks
we should remain wearing masks

one in 20 students being off school at the moment is the reason why we really need to maintain some of the restrictions

schools and the children have suffered so much and continue to suffer

there's huge disparity between children who are from kind of less privileged socio-economic backgrounds that have missed a year plus of education

we cannot go back

if we are to keep doing getting the liquids and saliva and the blood of animals on us

viruses will keep jumping from animals to people

with all of the rules put in place which we are all having to abide by, as Benjamin mentioned, family members who can't come together, weddings being postponed

there's a growing sense of inconsistency in the pandemic in terms of how rules are being applied

there were lots of pubs full of people breaking all the rules Andy Burnham is talking about

part of why people break the rules is because the leaders are not showing the way

Boris Johnson's non-action was or was not a missed opportunity to set the standard for social distancing

there has been a bit of comeback with Boris Johnson seen celebrating England's football goals

there are a few people organising weddings saying Boris Johnson doesn't remain seated if he is consuming food and drink

David Davis : I agree with the fact you have to provide leadership by your action as well as by what you say

David Davis : I want to see us get back as close as we can to usual

normal got us here

we do need a new way of doing things

Andy Burnham : We are building zero carbon homes

AudienceMember 20210708QT02 : to show us he does have a moral compass
